ance enclosing me brought out with oracular accuracyevery imperfection in my text. A memoirist has noted that not only did Islow down now and then while unclipping a pencil and replacing a comma by asemicolon, but that I had been known to stop and frown over a sentence andreread it, and cross it out, and insert a correction and "re-mouth the wholepassage with a kind of defiant complacency."

